A true sanctuary protecting the most exceptional floral species, including the wild ancestor of the Rose de Granville

Every day starts with a good breakfast, but for actress and @DiorMakeup face @CaraDelevingne, this is no ordinary day - it's the unveiling of the #DiorCouture Autumn-Winter 2021-2022 collection by @MariaGraziaChiuri. The book 'Threads of Life: A History of the World Through the Eye of a Needle' proved a starting point for @MariaGraziaChiuri spark for the #DiorCouture Autumn-Winter 2021-2022 collection. And here its author @SewingMatters discusses the overlooked importance of sewing as a millennia-old form of visual communication, a repository for ideas of identity and place, and a means of connecting people and of sharing ideas around the world. 
© Clare Hunter is a community textile artist, curator & author based in Scotland. Threads of Life is published by Sceptre, Hodder & Stoughton (UK), Abrams Press (US), Bollati Boringhieri (Italy) & Uitgeverij Balans (Amsterdam).

node.title: Reclaiming the outsized role of sewing

Uncover the awesome effort required to realize the 340m2 of embroideries that lined the show space for the unveiling of the #DiorCouture Autumn-Winter 2021-2022 collection by @MariaGraziaChiuri. The motifs of artist Eva Jospin's work, 'Chambre de Soie', were divided into panels and interpreted as free-flowing embroideries involving 150 different kinds of stitches and techniques, and undertaken by 300 artisans at the @Chanakya.School in Mumbai, India. Founded in 2017 by the @Chanakya.In ateliers, the school preserves exceptional techniques and empowers women in local communities by training them as master craftspeople, in India a role traditionally reserved for men. This collection is thus a celebration of the transmission and richness of savoir-faire, a collective work glorifying the borderless beauty of craft. 
© Film by @MelindaTriana

Meet Eva Jospin, the artist behind 'Chambre de Soie', the immense work that lined the show set for the #DiorCouture Autumn-Winter 2021-2022 collection by @MariaGraziaChiuri. She speaks about how her discovery of an embroidered room in a Roman palazzo would eventually lead to her collaboration with @Chanakya.School in Mumbai on translating her art into a creation composed of an eye-watering 340m2 of hand embroidery.
© Film by @MelindaTriana
Photo: Sophie Carre

Stay tuned to see its ultraglossy reinvention by @MariaGraziaChiuri.

node.text:
The #LadyDior bag made its first public appearance in late 1995, carried by Diana, Princess of Wales, upon landing in Buenos Aires, Argentina. In an image seen around the world, her unerringly elegant and contemporary look was flawlessly finished with her black leather handbag. Named in honor of her, its architectural lines, Cannage quilting and characteristic lettered charms would make it an instant object of desire, the first step on its journey to becoming the House's most iconic bag, with a design that's been endlessly reinvented ever since.
© Cherruault/SIPA

node.text:
Initially bearing the working name 'Chouchou' in the ateliers, the #LadyDior bag was propelled to stardom through its adoption by Diana, Princess of Wales, after whom it would come to be eventually named. Ever before its public launch, the bag was presented by the First Lady of France, Bernadette Chirac, to the princess on a visit to Paris in September 1995 for the inauguration of a Cézanne exhibition. After this auspicious start, the Cannage-quilted bag would go on to become one of her favorite and most photographed accessories, in the process cementing its iconic status as a byword for the modernity and creativity of the House's heritage.
© Antony Jones/UK Press/Getty Images
